The paper deals with efficient algorithms for computing rank-revealing factorizations of matrices that are too large to fit in RAM and must be stored on slow external memory devices. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Numerical Analysis (cs.NA) sub-category, which deals with algorithms and computational methods for solving mathematical problems. Additionally, the paper involves the use of randomized algorithms and power iterations, which are commonly used in the field of numerical linear algebra. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS), Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC), Scientific Computing (cs.SC), and Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-categories, which are all closely related to numerical linear algebra and involve the development of efficient algorithms for large-scale data processing.
